\section{The Purpose of the System}
The goal of this project is to develop an engaging, interactive FPGA-based battle game with minimised latency and a smooth user experience. Two FPGA nodes each serve as a combined battle-state calculator and video-output renderer. A cloud server acts as the central synchroniser, coordinating game state between both players in real time. The system is designed to maximise responsiveness while remaining extensible. Optional features such as audio-based move selection can be layered on top of the core architecture without disrupting the critical game loop.
\section{Overall Architecture of the System}
The system consists of two FPGA nodes and one cloud-based server, forming a distributed IoT architecture..
\newline
\subsection*{FPGAs}
Each FPGA node is responsible for latency-critical operations:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Capturing user input via the Jupyter Notebook interface
    \item Computing local game state updates (e.g., player actions)
    \item Rendering video output using hardware-accelerated pipelines
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Cloud Server}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Maintains the global game state shared between both players
    \item Resolves updates from both nodes
    \item Synchronises turns using a shared turn counter
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Communication Model}
Communication between FPGA nodes and the server is implemented using a polling-based approach:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Each FPGA periodically polls the server for updated game state
    \item FPGA nodes push local updates to the server after processing user actions
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{System Interaction Flow}
The interaction between components follows the sequence below:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The user selects an action via buttons displayed in the Jupyter Notebook interface
    \item The FPGA processes the input and computes the updated local battle state
    \item The updated state is transmitted to the server
    \item The server updates the global game state
    \item The second FPGA polls the server and retrieves the updated state
    \item The FPGA updates its registers and renders the new game state to the display
\end{enumerate}
Only valid actions are presented to the user, ensuring correctness of input and simplifying state management.
\subsection*{Concurrency Control}
To prevent race conditions, a turn-based locking mechanism is implemented using a shared turn counter. Only the FPGA corresponding to the active player is permitted to update the global state at any given time. This ensures consistency while avoiding conflicting updates.
