\section{The approach taken to test your system.}
We split the system into parts to test the system. We split the system into FPGA to Server communication, battle state calculation, FPGA to video output, and tested these subsystems separately before putting them together. We utilized our knowledge from previous labs to use a server and set it up so that the FPGA polls info from the server and loads it into registers. We implemented pushing info from FPGA to server at the same time. We rely on flags on the FPGA and those polled from the server to do certain actions and prohibit others. Using these flags and values loaded into the FPGA registers, we do battle state calculation. We send the battle state calculation over the server and after we re-poll the state from the server, we output video according to that. 
The other things are "extensions", meaning that they are not in the critical flow of the system and can be taken out if needed.
